…For the stats geeks: a random number distribution is just a probability distribution designed to take PRNG values as input.The random library has many random numbers distributions, most of which you will never use unless you’re doing some kind of statistical analysis. But there’s one random number distribution that’s extremely useful: auniform distributionis a random number distribution that produces outputs between two numbers X and Y (inclusive) with equal probability.Here’s a similar program to the one above, using a uniform distribution to simulate the roll of a 6-sided dice:#include <iostream>
#include <random> // for std::mt19937 and std::uniform_int_distribution

int main()
{
	std::mt19937 mt{};

	// Create a reusable random number generator that generates uniform numbers between 1 and 6
	std::uniform_int_distribution die6{ 1, 6 }; // for C++14, use std::uniform_int_distribution<> die6{ 1, 6 };

	// Print a bunch of random numbers
	for (int count{ 1 }; count <= 40; ++count)
	{
		std::cout << die6(mt) << '\t'; // generate a roll of the die here

		// If we've printed 10 numbers, start a new row
		if (count % 10 == 0)
			std::cout << '\n';
	}

	return 0;
}This produces the result:3       1       3       6       5       2       6       6       1       2
2       6       1       1       6       1       4       5       2       5
