Unfortunately, PRNGs can’t do this. They can only generate numbers that use the full range. What we need is some way to convert a number that is output from our PRNG into a value in the smaller range we want (with an even probability of each value occurring). While we could write a function to do this ourselves, doing so in a way that produces non-biased results is non-trivial.Fortunately, the random library can help us here, in the form of random number distributions. Arandom number distributionconverts the output of a PRNG into some other distribution of numbers.As an aside…For the stats geeks: a random number distribution is just a probability distribution designed to take PRNG values as input.The random library has many random numbers distributions, most of which you will never use unless you’re doing some kind of statistical analysis. But there’s one random number distribution that’s extremely useful: auniform distributionis a random number distribution that produces outputs between two numbers X and Y (inclusive) with equal probability.Here’s a similar program to the one above, using a uniform distribution to simulate the roll of a 6-sided dice:#include <iostream>
