If you initializestd::seed_seqwith a single value (e.g. fromstd::random_device) and then initialize a Mersenne Twister with thestd::seed_seqobject,std::seed_seqwill generate 623 values of additional seed data. This won’t add randomness, but it will give us a better mix of 0 and 1 bits. However, the more random data we can providestd::seed_seq, the better job it will do for us. So the easiest idea is to simply usestd::random_deviceto givestd::seed_seqmore data to work with. If we initializestd::seed_seqwith 8 values fromstd::random_deviceinstead of 1, then the remaining values generated bystd::seed_seqshould be much better:#include <iostream>
#include <random>

